    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "201a566f_59654d7b",
        "filename": "snapshot/ios/exception_snapshot_ios.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-24T15:20:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Seeing this juxtaposed against the much more capable InitializeCPUContextX86_64, I wonder why the ARM version isn’t more capable.\n\nFor example: InitializeCPUContextX86_64 consults its flavor argument to decide what to do with the passed-in context in its state argument. (It also validates the state_count.) If you had something that looked at flavor here, you would have found that arm_thread_state64_t was wrong.\n\nIn the x86 code, we’ve delegated a lot of the correct data shuffling and validation to InitializeCPUContextX86_64, so it doesn’t have to appear here (or in duplicate in the thread snapshot). But here, this isn’t doing the shuffling or validation, and neither is InitializeCPUContextARM64. That’s how bugs are born.",
      "revId": "362968ada558c3419190362d4fef9cad0e27b939",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
